<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="349" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,391,1175]" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">
<emphasis box="[151,273,391,416]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="349" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,391,416]" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">Diagnosis</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
A species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bleeker" authorityYear="1858" box="[432,609,392,416]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Lepidocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="349" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[432,609,392,416]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">Lepidocephalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that is readily distinguishable (
<figureCitation box="[970,1038,391,416]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,249,1690,1712]" captionTargetBox="[153,1434,151,1673]" captionTargetId="figure-188@2.[153,1438,141,1673]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Species of Lepidocephalus. (A) L. nanensis, holotype, NIFI 4388, 72.0 mm SL, Nan River, Thailand; (B) L. macrochir, syntype, BMNH 1866.5.2.55, 77.7 mm SL, Sumatra or Java; (C) L. pallens, holotype, RMNH 7783, 41.9 mm SL; (D) L. pahangensis, holotype, ZRC 490, 35.8 mm SL; (E) L. spectrum, paratype, USNM 230267, 49.2 mm SL, Kalimantan. Photos A, C, D and E by Z. Randall; B by M. Sabaj Perez." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4910405" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4910405/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<tableCitation box="[1054,1137,391,416]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="9.[151,241,476,499]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="TABLE 1. Characteristics that vary among species of Lepidocephalus. Measurements are in mm or percentages of standard length (SL). Range is followed by average in parentheses." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF5F6679FFC2DB25C0EF5DC05E6AA251" pageId="8" pageNumber="349" tableUuid="DF5F6679FFC2DB25C0EF5DC05E6AA251">Table 1</tableCitation>
) from other all species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bleeker" authorityYear="1858" box="[151,328,428,452]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Lepidocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="349" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,328,428,452]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">Lepidocephalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the absence of eyes, absence of dark pigment on the body, and presence of pored tubules along the lateral line. It further differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="van Hasselt, 1823" authorityName=", de Beaufort" authorityYear="1933" box="[577,747,464,488]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Acanthophthalmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="349" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pahangensis">
<emphasis box="[577,747,464,488]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">L. pahangensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of scales on top of the head, from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Vaillant" baseAuthorityYear="1902" box="[1325,1436,464,488]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Lepidocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="349" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pallens">
<emphasis box="[1325,1436,464,488]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">L. pallens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having the dorsal-fin origin slightly behind (vs. over) the pelvic-fin origin (predorsal length 62.4–65.6 vs. 59.9% SL), from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Deein &amp; Tangjitjaroen &amp; Page" authorityYear="2014" box="[267,394,536,560]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Lepidocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="349" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nanensis">
<emphasis box="[267,394,536,560]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">L. nanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having large papillae on the lips (
<figureCitation box="[805,902,535,560]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,249,945,967]" captionTargetBox="[165,1424,354,917]" captionTargetId="figure-182@5.[159,1428,350,920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Mouths of Lepidocephalus. (A) L. nanensis, holotype, NIFI 4388, 72.0 mm SL, Nan River, Thailand; (B) L. pahangensis, holotype, ZRC 490, 35.8 mm SL; (C) L. spectrum, paratype, USNM 230267, 49.2 mm SL, Kalimantan. Photos by Z. Randall." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4910409" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4910409/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">Figs. 3C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[914,950,535,560]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,249,1948,1970]" captionTargetBox="[170,1416,1104,1898]" captionTargetId="figure-185@5.[164,1422,1094,1898]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Mouths of specimens of Lepidocephalus shown in Figure 3. (A) L. nanensis, (B) L. spectrum. Although the lower lip of L. nanensis is folded more posteriorly than that of L. spectrum, it and the upper lip lack the large papillae shown on the lips of L. spectrum. Drawings by D. Lumbantobing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4910411" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4910411/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">4B</figureCitation>
), and from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bleeker" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[1077,1222,536,560]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Lepidocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="349" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrochir">
<emphasis box="[1077,1222,536,560]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">L. macrochir</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having a longer head (21.3–23.3 vs. 16.6–18.80).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="349" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,391,1175]" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">
<emphasis box="[199,344,607,632]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="349" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,607,632]" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">Description</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Body deep, slab-sided; greatest depth 18.9–22.1% SL. Head narrow, length 21.3–23.3% SL. Eye absent; small shallow depression above bifid suborbital spine where eye located on other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bleeker" authorityYear="1858" box="[151,328,680,704]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Lepidocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="349" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,328,680,704]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">Lepidocephalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Origin of dorsal fin slightly behind origin of pelvic fin. Small axillary lobe on pelvic fin. Large fleshy lobe at origin of pectoral fin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,391,1175]" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">Scales on top of head, cheek and opercle; body completely covered with minute, deeply embedded scales. Lateral line complete, 70–87 pores at ends of ventrally directed tubules along lateral line, 0–2 pores on caudal fin.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,391,1175]" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">
Mouth horseshoe-shaped; lips with large papillae on outer surfaces; upper lip without indentation; lower lip with median indentation on lower edge (
<figureCitation box="[602,700,860,885]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,249,945,967]" captionTargetBox="[165,1424,354,917]" captionTargetId="figure-182@5.[159,1428,350,920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Mouths of Lepidocephalus. (A) L. nanensis, holotype, NIFI 4388, 72.0 mm SL, Nan River, Thailand; (B) L. pahangensis, holotype, ZRC 490, 35.8 mm SL; (C) L. spectrum, paratype, USNM 230267, 49.2 mm SL, Kalimantan. Photos by Z. Randall." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4910409" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4910409/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">Figs. 3C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[712,748,860,885]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,249,1948,1970]" captionTargetBox="[170,1416,1104,1898]" captionTargetId="figure-185@5.[164,1422,1094,1898]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Mouths of specimens of Lepidocephalus shown in Figure 3. (A) L. nanensis, (B) L. spectrum. Although the lower lip of L. nanensis is folded more posteriorly than that of L. spectrum, it and the upper lip lack the large papillae shown on the lips of L. spectrum. Drawings by D. Lumbantobing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4910411" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4910411/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">4B</figureCitation>
). Two pairs of rostral barbels; inner pair reaching to corner of mouth, outer pair reaching past corner of mouth; one pair of maxillary barbels, reaching approximately to vertical at posterior end of groove containing suborbital spine. Large flap on anterior nostril.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,391,1175]" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">
Dorsal rays iii,8–9; pectoral rays 11–13; pelvic rays 6–7; anal rays ii,5–6; upper branched caudal rays 7–8; lower branched caudal rays 7–8; vertebrae 28 abdominal + 14–15 caudal = 42–43 total (
<bibRefCitation author="Roberts, T. R." box="[1133,1325,1004,1029]" pageId="8" pageNumber="349" pagination="1 - 210" refId="ref8105" refString="Roberts, T. R. (1989) The freshwater fishes of western Borneo (Kalimantan Barat, Indonesia). Memoirs of the California Academy of Sciences, 14, 1 - 210." type="journal article" year="1989">Roberts 1989:96</bibRefCitation>
). Pectoral fins less falcate than in other species; 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[601,616,1039,1053]" fontSize="6" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">nd</superScript>
ray longer than other rays. Pectoral fin 17.1–18.1% SL; pelvic fin 9.1– 12.0% SL.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,391,1175]" box="[199,1125,1114,1139]" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">
<emphasis box="[199,335,1114,1139]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="349" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1114,1139]" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">Coloration</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Roberts, T. R." box="[497,666,1114,1139]" pageId="8" pageNumber="349" pagination="1 - 210" refId="ref8105" refString="Roberts, T. R. (1989) The freshwater fishes of western Borneo (Kalimantan Barat, Indonesia). Memoirs of the California Academy of Sciences, 14, 1 - 210." type="journal article" year="1989">Roberts (1989)</bibRefCitation>
as being creamy or pinkish white in life.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,867,1150,1175]" pageId="8" pageNumber="349" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,391,1175]" box="[199,867,1150,1175]" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">
<emphasis box="[199,352,1150,1175]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="349" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1150,1175]" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">Distribution</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Kapuas River basin, western Borneo (
<figureCitation box="[784,854,1150,1175]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,249,1699,1721]" captionTargetBox="[153,1429,349,1673]" captionTargetId="figure-196@4.[151,1436,339,1677]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Distribution of specimens of Lepidocephalus examined." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4910407" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4910407/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="349">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
